06371nam a22008055i 9780824879457DE-B159720220302035458.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220302t20192019hiu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808248794577 a10.1515/97808248794572doi  a(DE-B1597)513317  a(OCoLC)1099791073  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ahiucUS-HI 4aPL721.F87bD56 2019eb 7aLIT0080302bisacsh04a895.63/609362231 aDiNitto, Rachel, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aFukushima Fiction :bThe Literary Landscape of Japan’s Triple Disaster /cRachel DiNitto. 1aHonolulu : bUniversity of Hawaii Press, c[2019] 4c©2019  a1 online resource (240 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction: Disaster Strikes, Literature Responds -- t1. Voices from the Debris: Cultural Trauma and Disaster Fiction -- t2. Tohoku on the Margins: Furukawa Hideo’s Horses -- t3. Hiroshima Encore: Return of the Hibakusha -- t4. Chernobyl and Beyond: A New Era of Nuclear Literature -- tEpilogue: Writing toward the Future -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex -- tAbout the Author0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aFukushima Fiction introduces readers to the powerful literary works that have emerged out of Japan’s triple disaster, now known as 3/11. The book provides a broad and nuanced picture of the varied literary responses to this ongoing tragedy, focusing on “serious fiction” (junbungaku), the one area of Japanese cultural production that has consistently addressed the disaster and its aftermath. Examining short stories and novels by both new and established writers, author Rachel DiNitto effectively captures this literary tide and names it after the nuclear accident that turned a natural disaster into an environmental and political catastrophe.The book takes a spatial approach to a new literary landscape, tracing Fukushima fiction thematically from depictions of the local experience of victims on the ground, through the regional and national conceptualizations of the disaster, to considerations of the disaster as history, and last to the global concerns common to nuclear incidents worldwide. Throughout, DiNitto shows how fiction writers played an important role in turning the disaster into a narrative of trauma that speaks to a broad readership within and outside Japan. Although the book examines fiction about all three of the disasters—earthquake, tsunami, and nuclear meltdowns—DiNitto contends that Fukushima fiction reaches its critical potential as a literature of nuclear resistance. She articulates the stakes involved, arguing that serious fiction provides the critical voice necessary to combat the government and nuclear industry’s attempts to move the disaster off the headlines as the 2020 Olympics approach and Japan restarts its idle nuclear power plants.Rigorous and sophisticated yet highly readable and relevant for a broad audience, Fukushima Fiction is a critical intervention of humanities scholarship into the growing field of Fukushima studies. The work pushes readers to understand the disaster as a global crisis and to see the importance of literature as a critical medium in a media-saturated world. By engaging with other disasters—from 9/11 to Chernobyl to Hurricane Katrina—DiNitto brings Japan’s local and national tragedy to the attention of a global audience, evocatively conveying fiction’s power to imagine the unimaginable and the unforeseen.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aFukushima Nuclear Disaster, Japan, 2011, in literature. 0aJapanese literaturey21st centuryxHistory and criticism. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Asian / Japanese.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertAsian Studies Cont